{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_277b437c3ffe5n8oKk7kMHeudS","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d884c2763001z9PJqYTBUL4GPf","parts":[{"id":"prt_d884c3180001Deuku53BmejBYe","messageID":"msg_d884c2763001z9PJqYTBUL4GPf","sessionID":"ses_277b437c3ffe5n8oKk7kMHeudS","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6fa4cc1afa1e41659af2edcf","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/lfs/manage/README.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/lfs/manage/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Technique: Tab-based Edit Views in Django\n2: \n3: ## Motivation\n4: \n5: - A complex object (e.g. Product, Category, StaticBlock) has multiple different data areas (tabs: master data, prices, SEO, files, …).\n6: - Each tab should be saved separately (POST processes only one form), so validation errors in one tab don't block the others.\n7: - The UI shows all tabs in the same shell template with navigation. Tab content is included via `{% include %}`.\n8: \n9: ---\n10: \n11: ## Architecture\n12: \n13: ### 1. Shell Template (Framework)\n14: \n15: - Contains tab navigation (`tabs`)\n16: - Contains a `#tab-content` area\n17: - Based on an `active_tab` variable that controls which partial is included.\n18: \n19: **Example: `templates/products/product_edit.html`**\n20: \n21: ```django\n22: <h1>Edit Product: {{ product.name }}</h1>\n23: \n24: <nav class=\"tabs\">\n25:   {% for key, url in tabs %}\n26:     <a href=\"{{ url }}\" class=\"{% if active_tab == key %}active{% endif %}\">\n27:       {{ key|title }}\n28:     </a>\n29:   {% endfor %}\n30: </nav>\n31: \n32: <div id=\"tab-content\">\n33:   {% if active_tab == \"data\" %}\n34:     {% include \"products/tabs/_data.html\" %}\n35:   {% elif active_tab == \"seo\" %}\n36:     {% include \"products/tabs/_seo.html\" %}\n37:   {% elif active_tab == \"files\" %}\n38:     {% include \"products/tabs/_files.html\" %}\n39:   {% endif %}\n40: </div>\n41: ```\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ### 2. Partials (Tab Contents)\n46: \n47: Each tab has a partial template that renders a form.  \n48: These receive their context directly from the view.\n49: \n50: **Example: `products/tabs/_data.html`**\n51: \n52: ```django\n53: <form method=\"post\">\n54:   {% csrf_token %}\n55:   {{ form.as_p }}\n56:   <button type=\"submit\">Save Data</button>\n57: </form>\n58: ```\n59: \n60: **Example: `products/tabs/_seo.html`**\n61: \n62: ```django\n63: <form method=\"post\">\n64:   {% csrf_token %}\n65:   {{ form.as_p }}\n66:   <button type=\"submit\">Save SEO</button>\n67: </form>\n68: ```\n69: \n70: ---\n71: \n72: ### 3. Shared Mixin\n73: \n74: A mixin builds the common context for all tabs: active tab, navigation, product object.\n75: \n76: **Example: `views_mixins.py`**\n77: \n78: ```python\n79: from django.urls import reverse\n80: from django.shortcuts import get_object_or_404\n81: from .models import Product\n82: \n83: class ProductTabMixin:\n84:     template_name = \"products/product_edit.html\"\n85:     tab_name = None  # set in subclass: \"data\", \"seo\", ...\n86: \n87:     def get_product(self):\n88:         return get_object_or_404(Product, pk=self.kwargs[\"pk\"])\n89: \n90:     def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):\n91:         ctx = super().get_context_data(**kwargs)\n92:         product = getattr(self, \"object\", None) or self.get_product()\n93:         ctx[\"product\"] = product\n94:         ctx[\"active_tab\"] = self.tab_name\n95:         ctx[\"tabs\"] = [\n96:             (\"data\", reverse(\"products:edit_data\", args=[product.pk])),\n97:             (\"seo\",  reverse(\"products:edit_seo\", args=[product.pk])),\n98:             (\"files\", reverse(\"products:edit_files\", args=[product.pk])),\n99:         ]\n100:         return ctx\n101: ```\n102: \n103: ---\n104: \n105: ### 4. Views per Tab\n106: \n107: #### Tab 1: Master Data (simple UpdateView)\n108: \n109: ```python\n110: from django.views.generic import UpdateView\n111: from django.urls import reverse\n112: from .forms import ProductForm\n113: \n114: class ProductDataView(ProductTabMixin, UpdateView):\n115:     model = Product\n116:     form_class = ProductForm\n117:     tab_name = \"data\"\n118: \n119:     def get_success_url(self):\n120:         return reverse(\"products:edit_data\", args=[self.object.pk])\n121: ```\n122: \n123: #### Tab 2: SEO (OneToOne Relation, UpdateView with get_object)\n124: \n125: ```python\n126: from .models import SEO\n127: from .forms import SEOForm\n128: \n129: class ProductSEOView(ProductTabMixin, UpdateView):\n130:     model = SEO\n131:     form_class = SEOForm\n132:     tab_name = \"seo\"\n133: \n134:     def get_object(self, queryset=None):\n135:         product = self.get_product()\n136:         seo, _ = SEO.objects.get_or_create(product=product)\n137:         return seo\n138: \n139:     def get_success_url(self):\n140:         return reverse(\"products:edit_seo\", args=[self.object.product.pk])\n141: ```\n142: \n143: #### Tab 3: Files (Upload + List, therefore FormView)\n144: \n145: ```python\n146: from django.views.generic import FormView\n147: from django.db import transaction\n148: from .models import StaticBlockFile\n149: from .forms import FileForm\n150: \n151: class ProductFilesView(ProductTabMixin, FormView):\n152:     form_class = FileForm\n153:     tab_name = \"files\"\n154: \n155:     def get_success_url(self):\n156:         return reverse(\"products:edit_files\", args=[self.kwargs[\"pk\"]])\n157: \n158:     def form_valid(self, form):\n159:         block = self.get_product()\n160:         with transaction.atomic():\n161:             file = form.save(commit=False)\n162:             file.block = block\n163:             file.save()\n164:         return super().form_valid(form)\n165: \n166:     def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):\n167:         ctx = super().get_context_data(**kwargs)\n168:         ctx[\"files\"] = self.get_product().files.all()\n169:         return ctx\n170: ```\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ### 5. URLs\n175: \n176: **Example: `urls.py`**\n177: \n178: ```python\n179: from django.urls import path\n180: from .views import ProductDataView, ProductSEOView, ProductFilesView\n181: \n182: app_name = \"products\"\n183: \n184: urlpatterns = [\n185:     path(\"<int:pk>/edit/data/\", ProductDataView.as_view(), name=\"edit_data\"),\n186:     path(\"<int:pk>/edit/seo/\", ProductSEOView.as_view(), name=\"edit_seo\"),\n187:     path(\"<int:pk>/edit/files/\", ProductFilesView.as_view(), name=\"edit_files\"),\n188: ]\n189: ```\n190: \n191: ---\n192: \n193: ## User Flow\n194: \n195: 1. Click on \"Data\" → `/edit/data/`  \n196:    → renders Shell + _data.html\n197: 2. Click on \"SEO\" → `/edit/seo/`  \n198:    → renders Shell + _seo.html\n199: 3. Click on \"Files\" → `/edit/files/`  \n200:    → renders Shell + _files.html\n201: \n202: - Always the same shell, only `active_tab` changes.\n203: - POST processes only the form of the active tab.\n204: \n205: ---\n206: \n207: ## Advantages of this Technique\n208: \n209: - Only **one central view** for the entire object\n210: - Good extensibility for additional tabs\n211: - Tab switching triggers a full request (no JS necessary)\n212: - Flexible markup via `{% include %}`\n213: \n214: ---\n215: \n216: ## Optional\n217: \n218: - Define tabs as URLs too: `/edit/?tab=data`, `/edit/?tab=files`\n219: - Form validation per tab\n220: - Integration of formsets or additional context data per tab\n221: \n222: ---\n223: \n224: ## Modal System\n225: \n226: ### Overview\n227: \n228: The management interface uses a size-specific modal system to provide optimal user experience. Instead of resizing modals dynamically (which causes visual flicker), we use dedicated modal snippets for different content types.\n229: \n230: ### Modal Snippets\n231: \n232: **Structure: `templates/manage/snippets/modals/`**\n233: \n234: ```\n235: modals/\n236: ├── modal-sm.html     # Small modals (confirmations, alerts)\n237: ├── modal-lg.html     # Large modals (forms, data entry)\n238: └── modal-xl.html     # Extra large modals (previews, complex content)\n239: ```\n240: \n241: **Example: `modal-lg.html`**\n242: \n243: ```django\n244: {% load i18n %}\n245: <div class=\"modal\" id=\"lfs-modal-lg\" tabindex=\"-1\" aria-hidden=\"true\">\n246:     <div class=\"modal-dialog modal-lg\">\n247:         <div class=\"modal-content\">\n248:             <div class=\"modal-header\">\n249:                 <h5 class=\"modal-title\" id=\"modal-title-lg\"></h5>\n250:                 <button type=\"button\" class=\"btn-close\" data-bs-dismiss=\"modal\" aria-label=\"{% trans 'Close' %}\"></button>\n251:             </div>\n252:             <div class=\"modal-body\" id=\"modal-body-lg\"></div>\n253:         </div>\n254:     </div>\n255: </div>\n256: ```\n257: \n258: ### JavaScript Integration\n259: \n260: **File: `static/lfs/js/management/shared.js`**\n261: \n262: ```javascript\n263: document.addEventListener('htmx:afterSwap', evt => {\n264:     const targetId = evt.detail.target?.id;\n265:     let modalEl;\n266:     \n267:     // Target-based modal selection\n268:     if (targetId === \"modal-body-sm\") {\n269:         modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-sm');\n270:     } else if (targetId === \"modal-body-lg\") {\n271:         modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-lg');\n272:     } else if (targetId === \"modal-body-xl\") {\n273:         modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-xl');\n274:     }\n275:     \n276:     if (modalEl) {\n277:         let modalInstance = bootstrap.Modal.getInstance(modalEl);\n278:         if (!modalInstance) {\n279:             modalInstance = new bootstrap.Modal(modalEl);\n280:         }\n281:         if (!modalEl.classList.contains('show')) {\n282:             modalInstance.show();\n283:         }\n284:     }\n285: });\n286: ```\n287: \n288: ### Usage in Templates\n289: \n290: **Button targeting specific modal size:**\n291: \n292: ```django\n293: <!-- For forms/data entry -->\n294: <button hx-get=\"{% url 'add_static_block' %}\" \n295:         hx-target=\"#modal-body-lg\"\n296:         hx-swap=\"innerHTML\">\n297:     Add Static Block\n298: </button>\n299: \n300: <!-- For previews/large content -->\n301: <button hx-get=\"{% url 'preview_static_block' pk %}\" \n302:         hx-target=\"#modal-body-xl\"\n303:         hx-swap=\"innerHTML\">\n304:     Preview\n305: </button>\n306: ```\n307: \n308: **Including modals in templates:**\n309: \n310: ```django\n311: {% extends \"manage/base.html\" %}\n312: \n313: {% block content %}\n314:     <!-- Your page content -->\n315:     \n316:     <!-- Include required modal sizes -->\n317:     {% include 'manage/snippets/modals/modal-lg.html' %}\n318:     {% include 'manage/snippets/modals/modal-xl.html' %}\n319: {% endblock %}\n320: ```\n321: \n322: **Modal content templates:**\n323: \n324: ```django\n325: <!-- add_static_block.html -->\n326: {% load i18n crispy_forms_tags %}\n327: \n328: <h5 id=\"modal-title-lg\" class=\"modal-title\" hx-swap-oob=\"true\">\n329:     {% trans 'Add Static Block' %}\n330: </h5>\n331: <form method=\"post\" hx-post=\"{% url 'add_static_block' %}\" hx-target=\"#modal-body-lg\">\n332:     {% csrf_token %}\n333:     {{ form|crispy }}\n334:     <div class=\"mt-3\">\n335:         <button type=\"submit\" class=\"btn btn-primary\">{% trans 'Save' %}</button>\n336:         <button type=\"button\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\" data-bs-dismiss=\"modal\">\n337:             {% trans 'Cancel' %}\n338:         </button>\n339:     </div>\n340: </form>\n341: ```\n342: \n343: ### Advantages\n344: \n345: **1. No Visual Flicker**\n346: - Fixed modal sizes prevent resize animations\n347: - Better user experience with instant, stable modals\n348: \n349: **2. Semantic Sizing**\n350: - Each modal size has a clear purpose:\n351:   - `modal-sm`: Quick confirmations, alerts\n352:   - `modal-lg`: Standard forms, data entry\n353:   - `modal-xl`: Content-heavy previews, complex displays\n354: \n355: **3. Performance**\n356: - No JavaScript modal resizing overhead\n357: - Modals initialize with final dimensions immediately\n358: \n359: **4. Maintainability**\n360: - Reusable modal snippets across templates\n361: - Centralized modal logic in `shared.js`\n362: - Clear separation of concerns\n363: \n364: **5. Extensibility**\n365: - Easy to add new modal sizes\n366: - Simple button-to-modal mapping via `hx-target`\n367: - Consistent pattern across the application\n368: \n369: ### Implementation Notes\n370: \n371: - Each modal has unique IDs (`lfs-modal-sm`, `lfs-modal-lg`, `lfs-modal-xl`)\n372: - Modal titles use size-specific IDs (`modal-title-sm`, `modal-title-lg`, `modal-title-xl`)\n373: - HTMX `hx-swap-oob=\"true\"` updates modal titles dynamically\n374: - JavaScript automatically detects target and shows appropriate modal\n375: \n376: This approach scales well and provides a consistent, flicker-free modal experience throughout the management interface.\n377: \n378: ## Note\n379: \n380: When tabs **become more complex** (e.g. many dependent fields, dynamic file uploads etc.), you can later switch to `htmx` or real `FormView` subcomponents.  \n381: The structure shown here works well as a scalable foundation for future expansion.\n382: \n383: # Frontend Dependencies and Vendor Assets\n384: \n385: Frontend libraries are managed through `package.json`. Running `npm run setup` first executes `npm install` to install all dependencies into `node_modules`, and then runs `npm run vendor:update`. The vendor update step starts by cleaning `static/lfs/manage/vendor/*` and then copies the required third-party assets (JavaScript, CSS, and fonts) from `node_modules` into `static/lfs/manage/vendor/...`.\n\n(End of file - total 385 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Technique: Tab-based Edit Views in Django\n\n## Motivation\n\n- A complex object (e.g. Product, Category, StaticBlock) has multiple different data areas (tabs: master data, prices, SEO, files, …).\n- Each tab should be saved separately (POST processes only one form), so validation errors in one tab don't block the others.\n- The UI shows all tabs in the same shell template with navigation. Tab content is included via `{% include %}`.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture\n\n### 1. Shell Template (Framework)\n\n- Contains tab navigation (`tabs`)\n- Contains a `#tab-content` area\n- Based on an `active_tab` variable that controls which partial is included.\n\n**Example: `templates/products/product_edit.html`**\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"lfs/manage/README.md","time":{"start":1776108188466,"end":1776108188471}}}]}
